The idea that leftism is somehow directly derived from Christianity is sloppy conceptual history, it would be just as trivial to reverse-engineer ideas like free migration out of paganism's extreme emphasis on hospitality, including tales of hosts offering their wives to guests.

It's the equivalent of tracing the concept of Lebensraum to the Old Testament and the Book of Joshua, just finding something that resembles an idea from centuries ago and drawing an arbitrary line between them. It's just not how conceptual history works.
Well those same stories exist in the Bible (Lot and his daughters) so a major case of friendly fire then
Logo is an ad absurdum example, but there are a lot of subtler and more deceptive ways this thinking creeps in

Not to stir any controversy, but people are way too uncharitable towards Chinese civilization, when Baron Julius Evola cites it as example of a traditional society every other page in "Revolt Against The Modern World", I think he only mentions Rome more often than Imperial China.

The Chinese literally saw the Emperor as natural phenomenon instead of a person, like the sun or a star. The concept of "balance" merely indicates the total ritualization of life, bringing it to the above-human dimension. Rites were seen as a Heavenly law reserved for patricians.

Moreover there are texts describing the ideal Chinese warrior as unaffected by passions and regarding defeat and victory equally, similar to the logic of the Crusades. The I Ching is of royal instead of priestly origin. China is an objectively Evolian civilization, up to a point.
